snippet.textDisplay: Exercise is one of those things that take a lifetime to perfect. There is always something that you can learn new about a particular exercise or a variation. I remember doing squats when i was younger  had a bunch of weight on the bar. A experienced weight lifter told me i had bad form and i need to go deeper down in the bucket. In order to do this i had to let go of all the weight , and start with the bar. Years later i squat with better form and more weight.  I learned sometimes in order to get better at something  have to put aside what you know for a time to get knowledge that can benifit. In order to do this you have to be humble.

snippet.textDisplay: Thank you for great, important tips on pull-ups. Been doing them off and on most of my adult life and just want to comment on the lower body rigidity you promote. For me, that absolutely would prevent me from doing as many pull-ups as I do now. I golf often and as in golf, tension is a killer in the golf swing. In pull-ups, I've learned that to maximize my reps, whatever is not being used to perform the exercise is totally relaxed. I only concentrate on my lats and arms (mainly triceps). For me, tension anywhere else is energy being drained and at my age, I need every bit of it. I feel from my hips down I'm 100% relaxed. On my first set I do at least 15 deliberate reps and can do over 20 if I had to. I do 4 sets as well as push ups and nothing else. My lower body workout is running and walking when I golf. I do as many pull-ups, maybe more, now than when I was in my 30's, when I felt I was in better shape. At 63, I feel I'm able to do as many reps as I do due to not being stronger, but smarter, doing what works for me. Good luck to you. Over 1.1 million views is nothing to sneeze at.

snippet.textDisplay:
It’s interesting, my training revolves around rock climbing, and for a good 6 months I focused on that with no accessory movements. After that time I incorporated accessory movements mainly as low level antagonist exercises focusing on building the strength of the antagonists rather than going for mass (since additional mass is a liability in climbing). Particularly after incorporating face pulls (or if a machine wasn’t available, isometric face pull style holds with a band) I began to do pull-ups differently. Simply by climbing and strengthening my antagonist muscles I found my pull-ups turned into exactly what Jeff is describing here. I used to hear bad sounds around my shoulders (just tendons passing over things, but still not good), then I started locking my shoulders with the increased lower trap strength from the face pulls. My lock-off ability (in climbing this is your endurance and ability to hold in the locked off position at the top of a pull up) exploded, I was doing one armed lock offs with both arms within a month of antagonist and accessory training. I still haven’t managed the elusive one-armed pull-up (though it hasn’t been a training focus) but can perform controlled eccentrics from the one arm lock off position in order to exercise the same muscles and connective tissue involved in the elusive movement.

All this is to say: listen to Jeff here. I’m someone who came to have impressive ability in the pull-up and had to work out all the cues Jeff describes in this video through trial and error, you don’t have to go through that now that this video exists.

snippet.textDisplay:
Totally agree with you, though I would like to discuss one point you made.

First, amazing video! You totally nail it when it comes to how to do a proper pull up. I thought I was doing them perfect and your take on them gave me some new pointers I can check in my own form, thank you!

Pullups are so underused and amazingly efficient. Kipping drives me nuts....

I only would like to add, I do think there is some value in changing hand position between sets. You make a great point, changing hand position engages other muscles than what a standard pullup hand position does, and I get that. I just think alternating hand positions does have some value.

And using a band.....absolutely...great advice. If it wasnt for the band, I never would have fallen in love with pullups. Every person beginning pullups needs a set of bands!

Thank you Jeff for your great videos!

snippet.textDisplay: Actually, your thoracic position at the top of the pull-up depends on your goals. If your goal is only to build the size of the lats, then yes, you can open your T-spine and still achieve a chin-over-bar pull-up. However, if you ever want to achieve higher skills, such as muscle-ups, you'll need to pull in a hollow position (with a flexed thoracic spine).
snippet.textOriginal: Actually, your thoracic position at the top of the pull-up depends on your goals. snippet.textDisplay:
My first exercise after warm up:
Monday: Squat (Intensity)
Tuesday: Rest Day
Wednesday: Bench Press (Intensity)
Thursday: Weighted Pull Up (Intensity)
Friday: Squat (Volume)
Saturday: Dip (Volume)
Sunday: Chin Up (Volume)


I switch intensity and volume with every second week. So then the week looks like this:


Monday: Squat (Volume)
Tuesday: Rest Day
Wednesday: Bench Press (Volume)
Thursday: Pull Up (Volume)
Friday: Squat (Intensity)
Saturday: Weighted Dip (Intensity)
Sunday: Weighted Chin Up (Intensity)


So I do equal amount of high intensity and high volume training. This type of schedule works for me.
I also have a second training session every day at evening 6-8 hours after the first workout and then I train 30min abs and 20min forearms. Except I don't do forearms on push days because next day is pull day and I need a good grip then. All my days are different during the week no pull day is the same or push day or leg day. I try to avoid doing the exactly same exercise twice a week but some exercises like squat and leg press etc are done twice.


Sometimes I surprise my muscles with a new exercise or do the workout backwards or whatever comes to my mind with a goal to not get used to the workout. I have no plan how much I lift before I enter the gym. Only the exercises are planned. I decide how I train during warm up when I feel what condition my body is in.


Athlean-X has influnced my workout program almost entirely and all the results I've gained with this workout (that I will make better as I get wiser and too used to it) is gained with the help of Athlean-X's YouTube videos for FREE. Without Athlean-X I would have broken my body with stupid intensive all-in on every set's rep everyday thinking but now I train smart yet intensively and high volume and I feel so good every day while having insanely fast gains so THANK YOU JEFF!
